{#
  Example 07 — Two-way binding equivalent (onChange callback).

  Nunjucks doesn't have reactive bindings like Svelte / Vue / React.
  The closest equivalent is the `onChange` callback on the client.js,
  combined with the consumer maintaining whatever store they want to
  keep in sync. Below, we mirror the active theme into a `<output>`
  element that sits outside the control.

  This is the recipe for "use the control like v-model:value" without
  a framework.

  Note: the control already owns a hidden input (named by `opts.name`,
  default "theme") that the client keeps in sync with the applied
  slug. If your form wraps the control, that input is submitted for
  free and you do not need a second one. Use `onChange` for anything
  living outside the form — mirrors, analytics, server sync.

  There is no "change" event to listen for: selection happens through
  the button and the listbox, not a native <select>. `onChange` is the
  supported hook.
#}
{% from "../theme-select.njk" import themeSelect %}

{#
  Wrapping the control in the <form> is all the "binding" a form
  needs: the macro's own hidden input (name="theme") carries the
  value, the client keeps it current, and it is pre-filled
  server-side so it submits correctly even if the client.js never
  runs. No second hidden input required.
#}
<form id="prefs">
    {{ themeSelect({
        label: "Theme",
        themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
        themes: ["light", "dark", "abyss"],
        storageKey: "my-app:theme"
    }) }}

    <button type="submit">Save preferences</button>
</form>

{# For anything outside the form, use onChange. #}
<p>
    Current theme:
    <output id="theme-output">(resolving…)</output>
</p>

<script type="module">
    import { autoInit } from "../theme-select.client.js";
    autoInit({
        onChange(slug) {
            document.getElementById("theme-output").textContent = slug;
        },
    });
</script>
